<DOC><DOCNO> AP890725-0305 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2210EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-EntertainmentGroup     07-25 0147</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Entertainment Group,0153</SECOND><HEAD>MCEG Plans To Buy London-Based Distributor</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Independent film producer Management CompanyEntertainment Group Inc. said it plans to purchase London-basedfilm distributor Virgin Vision Ltd. for $83 million.   The acquisition would greatly expand the operations of the5-year-old MCEG in the lucrative overseas markets, giving it accessto a film library that includes the United Kingdom rights to suchOrion movies as ``Robocop.''   MCEG plans to buy Virgin Vision from parent company Virgin GroupLtd. with $55 million in cash and $7.5 million in debt.   In addition, Virgin Group will receive 5.4 million shares ofMCEG stock at $3.75 per share, making Virgin Group the largestminority shareholder of MCEG, the company said.   MCEG, involved in film production, marketing and talentmanagement, released ``The Chocolate War.'' Its upcoming releasesinclude ``Convicts'' with Robert Duvall and ``Boardwalk'' withSally Kellerman.</TEXT></DOC>